[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I had no rest in my spirit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Instead of coming himself straight from Ephesus, as he had at first intended, and had intimated probably in the lost letter of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Corinthians 5:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or by Timotheus (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Corinthians 4:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or pressing on through Macedonia, as he purposed when he wrote the First Epistle (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Corinthians 16:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), he had sent on Titus (himself possibly connected with Corinth: see Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to ascertain what had been the effects of that Epistle on the Corinthian Church. Titus was to return to him at Troas. Not meeting him there, St. Paul, in his eager anxiety to hear something more than Timotheus had been able to tell him, left Troas, in spite of the opening which it presented for his work as a preacher of the gospel, and hastened on into Macedonia. Taking the route that he had taken before, he would probably go to Philippi, where he would find St. Luke; and we may conjecture, without much risk of error, that it was there that he and Titus met.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2:12-17 A believer's triumphs are all in Christ. To him be the praise and glory of all, while the success of the gospel is a good reason for a Christian's joy and rejoicing. In ancient triumphs, abundance of perfumes and sweet odours were used; so the name and salvation of Jesus, as ointment poured out, was a sweet savour diffused in every place. Unto some, the gospel is a savour of death unto death. They reject it to their ruin. Unto others, the gospel is a savour of life unto life: as it quickened them at first when they were dead in trespasses and sins, so it makes them more lively, and will end in eternal life. Observe the awful impressions this matter made upon the apostle, and should also make upon us. The work is great, and of ourselves we have no strength at all; all our sufficiency is of God. But what we do in religion, unless it is done in sincerity, as in the sight of God, is not of God, does not come from him, and will not reach to him. May we carefully watch ourselves in this matter; and seek the testimony of our consciences, under the teaching of the Holy Spirit, that as of sincerity, so speak we in Christ and of Christ.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I had no rest in my spirit - I was disappointed, sad, deeply anxious. Though the work in which I was engaged was that which usually gives me my highest joy, yet such was my anxiety to learn the state of things in Corinth, and the success of my letter, and to see Titus, whom I was expecting, that I had comparatively no peace, and no comfort.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But taking my leave of them - Though so many considerations urged me to stay; though there was such a promising field of labor, yet such was my anxiety to hear from you, that I left them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I went from thence into Macedonia - see the note, Acts 16:9. I went over where I expected to find Titus, and to learn the state of your affairs. This is one of the few instances in which Paul left an inviting field of labor, and where there was a prospect of signal success, to go to another place. It is adduced here to show the deep interest which he had in the church at Corinth, and his anxiety to learn what was their condition. It shows that there may be cases where it is proper for ministers to leave a field of great and inviting usefulness, to go to another field and to engage in another part of the great vineyard. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "I went from thence into Macedonia - see the note, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 16:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". I went over where I expected to find Titus, and to learn the state of your affairs. This is one of the few instances in which Paul left an inviting field of labor, and where there was a prospect of signal success, to go to another place. It is adduced here to show the deep interest which he had in the church at Corinth, and his anxiety to learn what was their condition. It shows that there may be cases where it is proper for ministers to leave a field of great and inviting usefulness, to go to another field and to engage in another part of the great vineyard. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "13. no rest in my spirit—rather, \"no rest for my spirit\" (Ge 8:9). As here his \"spirit\" had no rest; so in 2Co 7:5, his \"flesh.\" His \"spirit\" under the Holy Spirit, hence, concluded that it was not necessary to avail himself of the \"door\" of usefulness at Troas any longer.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "taking … leave of them—the disciples at Troas.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " He tells us, that when he came there, he was much troubled because he did not find his brother Titus; where the humility of this great apostle is considerable, in that he disdained not to call ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
