        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 8:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 12:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") had been sent by the Apostle to superintend the ‘collection for the saints’ at Corinth (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 16:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He was most probably the bearer of the former Epistle, and was anxiously expected by the Apostle (ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to bring information regarding the effect it had had upon the Corinthian Church. Though Titus is not mentioned in the Acts of the Apostles, he possessed in a high degree the confidence of the Apostle (ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as is shewn by his taking the chief place—he seems even to have held a position of greater prominence than ‘the brother whose praise is in the Gospel throughout all the Churches’ (ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")—in this important mission. Before this, he, as a Gentile, had been the subject of some discussion between St Paul and the Judaizing party at Jerusalem. The latter maintained that Titus ought to be circumcised, the former that he ought not; but St Paul carried his point. His character seems to have been one of deep earnestness and zeal (ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 8:16-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") calculated to win the confidence of the great Apostle. He was afterwards placed in charge of the church in Crete, and in this capacity received from St Paul a letter of instruction known as the Epistle to Titus. The last mention of him in point of date is in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", when he is said to have ‘departed to Dalmatia,’ doubtless on a mission. For the Apostle’s feelings on this occasion (ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:5-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") compare a similar anxiety displayed at an earlier period of his Apostolic career in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 3:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 3:5-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I went from thence into Macedonia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 20:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Εἰς Μακεδονίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to Macedonia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") where I would be nearer and might be sooner informed [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "what was the fruit of my former epistle to you",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—V. g.]—These topics are continued at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : and a most noble digression is here introduced in respect to events, which had in the meantime occurred and sufferings which had been endured by him elsewhere: the benefit of which he makes to flow even towards the Corinthians, whilst he hereby prepares the way for a defence against the false apostles.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 13.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I had;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "I have had",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The perfect vividly realizes the scene through which he had passed. I had no rest. St. Paul had evidently told Titus to come from his mission to Corinth and meet him at Troas. But either St. Paul reached the town earlier than he intended, or Titus had been delayed. Now, the apostle was so intensely eager to know how his rebukes had been received - the name of \"Corinth\" was so deeply engraven on his heart - he could so ill endure the thought of being on angry terms with converts which he so deeply loved, that the non-appearance of Titus filled him with devouring anxiety and rendered him incapable of any other work. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "In my spirit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to my spirit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It was the loftiest part of St. Paul's nature  - his spirit - which was utterly incapacitated from effort by the restlessness of his miserable uncertainty about the Corinthian Church. The disclosure of such feelings ought to have had a powerful influence on the Corinthians. We see from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 3:5, 9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that St. Paul yearned for tidings of his converts with an intensity which can hardly be realized by less fervent and self-devoted natures. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I found not Titus my brother.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Not only \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " brother,\" but \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "my",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " brother;\" the man whom in matters of this kind I most trusted as an affectionate and able fellow worker (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 8:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 12:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Titus, though not mentioned in the Acts, is the most prominent person in this Epistle, and it is evident that St. Paul felt for him a warm affection and respect (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 7:13, 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 8:16, 17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Taking my leave of them;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the Christians in Troas. The word for \"taking leave\" is also found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Into Macedonia.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " As he had intended to do (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 16:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 20:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He had doubtless told Titus to look out for him at Philippi, and expected to meet him there on his way to Troas. 2 Corinthians 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
